The most fitting category for this segment is **Eating**. 

The images show a group of people gathered around a table laden with food and drinks. Several individuals are actively engaged in consuming food, indicated by plates with food, people holding utensils, and some with their mouths open as if eating. The overall scene depicts a mealtime gathering.
transcript: Allegedly track you did, you remember? Multimedia Event Detection was? Yeah. And that was what they call summarization. It was a bit of a blasphemy to call it summarization because it was just evidence. Yeah, exactly. I mean, I guess you can get to multiple levels. You can just provide an explanation and say, because I have seen those things on three pictures, that's how I come... Or you really provide the list of evidence and say, this is the picture, this is the picture. Yeah, you can provide the stat and the time stat. That's asynchronous then, right? Metatask was asynchronous. Yeah, I mean you could do it in a synchronous thing as well if you have a system doing it. But of course if you do that in an interactive way and you have these things that that the user reasoned and the system doesn't know about then it gets difficult yeah but but at least I mean I guess it could be interesting to to build a system that also can keep this evidence so basically that when you provide the answer you have the things you looked at and say well, this is the information I used to come up with the answer. I would like to bring an additional aspect to this discussion because the the grand challenge traditionally was always funded by companies and in a way that they also get some output, right? Even though I fully agree with all of you that we need interactive challenges, I think for the grand challenge at ACM Multimedia we could also maybe do some subtasks like labeling. For example, many people in multimedia are working on food recognition. So it could be a collaborative annotation task also. And then on that collaborative annotation we could extract metadata later on maybe use it for the interactive challenges as a ground truth even though it might not be completely correct yes but as a challenge you put it as a challenge how do you evaluate I mean the challenge has kind of this competition character Yeah, exactly. There's more hackathon, yeah. Let me know what came up at that meeting in HTML3 on the first morning. It was a health-based hackathon is what they wanted to do. And we're naturally going to feed into that if we use this data. I mean there's some very interesting things we can do about this. I mean, for example, all of these things have barcodes on them. Right, right, right. So you can cross-reference this with the international product database and know exactly what this was. And then you can track how much of this happens to be fresh milk by Apple. How much of this was consumed over what amount of time. And, I mean, essentially, it will be difficult to track who actually consumed what. But the methodology would be applicable if you have a smaller group of people. For your health tracking, you can say, okay, what did I actually eat? What is my nutritional profile just based on things I've seen.
